Feb 15 2009 	The Art 	I was booked into this hotel for a transit stay, just one overnight, and was upgraded into one of the Art &amp; Tech rooms, which I have to say are marvelous. Nice, functional design with blond woods, a very work-friendly curved desk surrounded by electrical outlets that fit any kind of plug, and lighting that detects your movements with motion sensors and turns on soft lighting ahead of you.... no fumbling for bathroom lights. There was a glass walled rain shower that served as a separator between the main room's and the bathroom - it was frosted glass but could be somewhat awkward if you shared a room and your mate let the room service cart in while you were showering ;-) Very convenient to the airport, and food was good even in the lobby bar. Downsides.... expensive internet charge, and the atmosphere was a little cavernous and big-resortish. if you love big resorts, that is ok, but given Le Meridien's location far away from a beach, I can't see choosing this as a holiday accommodation. Reception and restaurant staff were very good. At check in, which was done by one of the staff that accompanied me from the the lobby directly to my room, I was offered a complimentary drink. I asked for apple juice. When the reception person came back with my credit card, she said &quot;juice is coming right up&quot; but it never appeared. Porters were speedy. I appreciate the free airport transfer, but this only applies to Terminal 1 - if you fly in or out of Terminal 2 you are on your own! I think I got good value, but this may be because I got upgraded to a very nice room. The Art &amp; Tech rooms are nicely decorated, high quality towels and sheets, and a very comfortable bed. I wish I had had more time to actually sleep in the bed on my layover and to explore the hotel a little more. What I saw of the pool area looked welcoming, and had I not been traveling alone I would have been tempted to try one of the several interesting restaurants on the grounds. One maintenance item of note: the rain showers are mounted directly in the drywall of the bathroom ceiling, which is already showing signs of water damage or leaky spots. And the full body shower mounted on one wall of the shower shoots out stinging needle-like jets of water that cannot be adjusted for a softer spray. Design of the shower is pure decadence, but execution of the construction could have been better. Still, it was a very nice bathroom altogether.	
