Oct 27 2008 	Had a great stay but room was below expectations	We used to live in Dubai, and although we had never stayed at Le Meridien near the airport, we had been there for meals a couple of times and it seemed a nice place. So, we were happy to book to stay for four nights in mid-August in a club room, which included complementary airport transfers, and use of the club lounge and business centre. When we made our booking I had included a request for a small gesture of some type from the hotel as the trip was to mark our wedding anniversary, and I asked for a late check in and specified our arrival time.We landed on time, but when we got to the Meridien desk at the airport, our car was not there. This was apparently because they did not have our flight number, but I was never asked to supply this, and I had included our arrival time in my special request with the booking, although the booking was not direct with the hotel. Anyway, the car arrived within about 10 minutes and the guy on the desk was extremely professional and courteous. The car was a Mercedes S350 with full leather etc., and we found ourselves wishing that the hotel wasn’t so close to the airport so we could enjoy the luxurious car a bit longer. One of the Reception staff accompanied the driver, and they both enquired about our journey etc and were very courteous. The journey was only a few minutes mainly using the back roads, but the driver was smooth and safe, something you always have to be thankful for in the Middle East!We were delivered to the Club entrance at the rear of the hotel, and our baggage taken care of. The same lady who was with us in the car took us directly to our room, and on the way pointed out the club facilities. Check-in was conducted in the room itself, with only minimal forms to complete. Our passports were delivered back within minutes once they had been copied. We had to give a credit card so they could imprint it for possible incidental expenditure of up to 2000 Dirhams, but this was not a problem. Overall the check-in process was extremely smooth. We also got a nice surprise in the room, as there was a chocolate cake, a bottle of wine and a vase of 6 fresh red roses in recognition of our anniversary, so we were really pleased with the effort the hotel made on that score.The room itself was a bit of a let down in some ways. The bathroom was the smallest I have seen in a 5 star hotel anywhere, and considering it was a club room, the bathroom was actually really poor. If two of you go in at the same time, prepare for some manoeuvering around and squeezing yourself against the wall to make some room. The wall-mounted hairdryer was close to useless (according to my wife), but we found out from a regular guest that Reception will readily give you a decent powerful one on request.The room was decorated in a pretty non-descript boring style, but the bed base matched the fabric wall panels and the 2 armchairs. That sounds nice enough until you look closer. It was pale blue cheap nylon, and the 2 armchairs covered in the tacky stuff belong in a 2 star hotel not a 5 star hotel club room. The stitching was also fraying on the arms of the armchairs. Did this spoil our stay? No of course not, but it is not exactly what you expect from a chain like Le Meridien and a 5 star hotel at 5 star prices. Maybe they are going to refurbish the rooms. The more expensive Art rooms, which we saw a glimpse of as they were being cleaned, look modern and attractive but we couldn’t tell if the bathroom was any bigger or better. On the plus side the bed linen was good quality and the bed comfortable, there is a tea and coffee machine with supplies, a flat screen TV and a minibar. The aircon was efficient and not particularly noisy. There was a sliding door leading the gardens, and a small patio outside of the room with a table and two garden chairs. Our room looked onto the tennis courts. Next time we would ask for a room on the other side, where it looks onto one of the pools. One strange omission was that there was no alarm clock/radio which is standard these days. We could not fault the housekeeping staff for their professionalism though – the room was spotlessly clean and supplies always replenished. On arrival you fill out some cards, one to choose your room cleaning time, and another for your preferences about which fruit you want every day in your room and what types of canapés and their delivery time. These are nice touches.The club lounge was nice enough, with a flat screen TV, armchairs and tables and chairs, and a bar. The service was excellent, courteous and on the right side of attentive rather than intrusive. Breakfast is served there, and you can afternoon tea and evening drinks, all included. Our only negative comment was that the aircon seemed to be set very low, and my wife found it so cold (despite a jumper) that we didn’t actually spend too much time in there. However, I would not use my wife as a good temperature benchmark, as like me most people in there seemed very comfortable sitting in shorts. If you are the sociable type, there always seemed to be a handful of people in the lounge chatting and swapping travel stories.The business centre was unusual in that all 4 computers were in full working order and the internet connection was really fast – my experience in most business centres is that you find at least one of the computers broken and the “broadband” slower than dial up!We spent one day round the pool. It has plenty of sun loungers, a Jacuzzi, a pool bar, toilets and a lifeguard, and a nice wooden bridge that crosses over the top of it. It was perfect for lazing around enjoying the sun and a few drinks. The lunch snack we ordered was also very tasty, and as usual the service was very good. There are at least 2 other pools, but we didn’t try themWe could not write this review without mentioning our visit to the Al Mijana restaurant for dinner. It serves Lebanese cuisine and came highly recommended. I don’t know if it is just Thursdays or every night, but the only choice was a set menu. It is the only time in my life when I have been to a restaurant and left feeling utterly bemused and embarrassed. The set menu was a mezzeh, which is a load of small dishes of different types served with bread. For those who haven’t mezzeh, the closest thing I can think of is Spanish tapas – hopefully that will give an idea.However, at Al Mijana they take it to a whole new level compared to our previous experiences of mezzeh. As far as we could count, there were about 18 cold dishes and another 4 hot dishes, plus a non-stop supply of delicious warm Arabic bread and a huge bowl of whole salad items (cucumber, carrots, salad leaves etc., and somewhat bizarrely half a cabbage!) If these dishes had been small (adequate for 2 people) there would be not be a great problem, but they weren’t. We were astonished at the amount of food put before us. It is no exaggeration at all to say that there was enough for definitely 6 people and probably 8, so of course even through we ate much more than we would usually, there was literally a mountain of food left uneaten. And then they brought the dessert, which was 3 different types of sweet cakes, half a dozen apples and pears, a large bowl of strawberries, and then bowls of grapes and plums. Again, there was enough there for about 8 people. While the unused fruit is probably recycled, the hot and cold uneaten mezzeh will be just thrown away. This monumental waste of food was the reason for our embarrassment, because around the world and even in Dubai there are people without enough to eat, and yet delicious nutritious food was going to waste in front of our eyes. The service was great, the food quality excellent, and the restaurant very pretty, but we won’t be going back unless it is to eat a la carte. Maybe these things wouldn’t bother most people, but living in the Middle East and seeing some of the squalid poverty and hunger some people (especially the unskilled labourers) have to endure, the meal left us very uncomfortable.2 further points to bear in mind – smoking (including shisha, the smell of which leaves my wife almost heaving she finds it that disgusting) is allowed, so if you are a non-smoker, expect your meal to be in a smoky atmosphere, especially if you eat later when the majority of the locals eat. Wine – the wine list was quite extensive, but the prices, even for Dubai, were eye-popping. Normally restaurants have 3 or 4 bottles for between 190 and 350 Dirhams (£34 to £62), so those of more modest means can still enjoy a reasonable bottle of wine (these are wines which would be roughly about £5 to £8 in a UK supermarket). At La Mijana we stuck with water. We are certainly not wine experts but we got chatting to a guy at the hotel who seemed to be well-travelled and very knowledgeable on wine, and he was scathing about the wine list prices at La Mijana, saying that they were an absolute rip-off for the quality, and that was in August, way before the recent collapse in the Sterling exchange rate which made the wine even more expensive. Buyer beware on that one. All in all we enjoyed our stay, and we would gladly go back. It was peaceful and relaxing, the service was excellent, and the facilities very good. Although the airport was relatively close by, we were amazed that we hardly noticed any aircraft noise at all. The only disappointment was the bathroom and the room decor, and these things have taken it down from rating it 5 to 4 on Tripadvisor for us.	
