Aug 6 2008	Don't turn up early!!!	This was my fourth visit to Le Meredien - the first two with my husband and the last two visits with a female friend. Perhaps it was the timing of the plane's arrival which was different the first time because we were dealt with very quickly at reception and then whisked along to our room. Our visits were without event and we had a lovely time. So lovely, I persuaded my girl friend to pay quite a bit more than she wanted to to stay there with me when I returned this year. We arrived on an early morning flight from Australia and even after we'd taken our time checking through the usual formalities and awaiting the arrival of the Meridien car, it was still only 7am when we arrived at the hotel. Naturally, we were told our room wasn't available and to wait 'a few minutes' for a vacancy. The 'short wait' lasted almost 5 hours. We were later informed that check in time is 'usually after mid-day' . There is a tendency for long haul flights to arrive at Dubai in the early hours of the morning and I do advise all passengers flying from Australia to be subsequently conscious of the long wait for hotel rooms and if a 5-6 hour wait in a hotel lobby after a 14 hour flight sounds horrendous (and it is!) to consider booking accommodation from the previous night (which can be an added expense and begs the question of whether this will make much difference), or choosing a '24-hour' hotel (which are few and far between). When we returned to Australia in July we endured the same wait. For readers who think I'm diabolical expecting a room to be available that early in the morning I should say that this treatment is not discretionary: two British families with young children who arrived at 8am, having paid for the previous night's accommodation, waited over two hours for their rooms: this suggests that the hotel is well aware not only of the flights which guests are booked on but also their estimated times of arrival. Therefore, it is likely that even if you have booked a room the night before but are not expected to arrive until the following day, your room will be allocated to another guest and you will have to wait until at least 10am before they vacate and the room has been cleaned. That apart, it is fair to say that this is a very good hotel - although I believe it's services are closer to 4* rather than 5* level. The hotel has good pools, an Irish pub (serving good cheapish food) and several other restaurants besides. I have eaten previously at the pub but this time chose to eat at the Thai restaurant - good food and moderately priced. However, even at 7.30pm we appeared to be the only people eating in any of the restaurants - whilst the pub was booked out. The hotel's breakfast is absolutely superb - even has a chocolate fountain. Staff are very attentive and service is efficient. If I had one gripe, it's that although we were out of our room for 4 hours and asked for it to be 'made up' this did not happen until early evening. As well, we received 'turn down' of our beds only once in four days. It might be a good idea when booking accommodation in Dubai to check with Emirates Airways or your travel agent to see whether Le Meridien has a small fee for offering rooms earlier - it will certainly help you to get over the jet lag more quickly.	
