Jan 24 2007 	Convenient to the Dubai airport	I returned to the Le Meridien (airport location) for another stay in December, 2006. The hotel seems to constantly be undergoing some form of renovation, and the design and lobby are definitely dated. For this stay, I was in the club section of the hotel which provided access to a private lounge with complimentary drinks and very limited snacks (usually nuts) in the early evening. The rooms are comfortable but can be noisy depending on the direction that they are facing. The rooms are all on the ground level of the building, and some face the nearby Dubai airport while others face a mosque with regular and loud prayer calls. A highlight of the hotel is the outstanding selection of restaurants within and adjacent to the property. I have tried many of the restaurants over several stays, and have never been disappointed. It is also possible to walk to the adjacent Al Bustan Rotana hotel, which has additional restaurants available. The Thai restaurant and the Hong-Kong style seafood restaurant at the Meridien are highly recommended options. The gym is above average, and there are three pools within the complex which are average for the area. This location is recommended for business travelers, especially those with a layover or short stay in Dubai.	
Jan 15 2007 	Champagne Christmas in the Art + Tech Meridien Rooms	My partner and I booked a six night stay direct with Le Meridien Dubai (airport) online for a short break over Christmas.Arriving late (2am) into Dubai this hotel is a great choice; the reception desk in the airport arrivals hall whisked away our luggage onto the complimentary shuttle bus, and we were into the lobby within five minutes, luggage re-appearing just as we completed the in room check-in.I had booked one of the upgraded rooms (there are presently 42 Art + Tech Rooms of the 383 total rooms in the hotel, at a price of 600AED, which switched to 1200AED the last two nights, the closer we got to New Year's Eve, and these are well worth paying for if you are staying a few days). Art + Tech category is different from the Royal Club, which are &quot;deluxe&quot; rooms, old fashioned, but do come with Club Room access.This hotel does not participate in the Starwood Preferred Guest programme, so no points for my stay, but my SPG Gold was acknowledged on check in.No problems checking in as two guys sharing a double bed, and the dedicated Art + Tech receptionist is particularly helpful with any questions you may have as a gay couple, though naturally discretion is required to respect local culture.Thursday evenings at the outdoor bar in this hotel, which attracts many cabin crew, is well worth a visit, and combines perfectly with the Laurent Perrier all-you-can-drink Champagne Buffet in the main Yalumba Restaurant every Thursday, a bargain!My Art+Tech package included a free bottle of wine, fruit platter and in room water, complimentary soft drinks/tea/coffee in the lobby bar all day, with free cocktails between 7pm and 8pm every night. We each had a token for a foot massage in the spa (superb), the gym was excellent with plenty of up to date cardio machines and weights, much needed as the sumptuous breakfast was also thrown in; do ask for pork bacon which they can easily provide.Though close to the airport I heard only one plane the whole time I was there; construction (renovating more rooms to become Art + Tech) was very quite and only noticeable one afternoon by one of the three pools when some drilling took place, but the low rise spread out nature of the hotel means you will not hear this in your room; can easily move from your sunbed if inconvenienced during the day; we stayed put.All rooms are non Smoking in accordance with Meridien policy; book a ground floor room and you can walk out into the well maintained grounds from your room if need be.Brand new Art+Tech rooms looked just like the photos on the website; Hermes toiletries (and plenty of them), sizeable bath, bidet, superb seperate shower with multiple jets AND a massive rain-effect shower rose in addition - the best shower I have ever had! Plenty of cupboard and desk space, robes and slippers, multi region DVD player (bring some along!) for the huge flat screen TV, evening turndown service, great coffee machine, swift room service and super comfy beds. WiFi access was fast and also included in my rate. Both a chair and a sofa; plenty of space in the room. Hi-tech lighting system was sometimes tricky to work out, and I am no technophobe.Though I am not a fan of the beach, you can get the complimentary shuttle which leaves daily for Le Royal Meridien; it takes an hour through infamous Dubai traffic, but if you are keen it's a nice way of visiting the beach without paying beach side prices, especially important during the expensive Christmas period.Staff were super friendly and could not do enough to help - had a personal email from the manager as I commented on a few small cosmetic areas where the finish in my room was not quite 100% (with an interior designer's eye you notice more than the average guest might, there was a missing seal round a light fitting...). With 14 restaurants you hardly have to leave the complex.VERDICT: Great for a pool-centric alternative to beachside properties, especially if arriving late. Book an Art+Tech room if staying longer than one night, and try and get a package which includes the extras listed here.	
