Nov 12 2006 	Fantastic Seafood Buffet	Recently we had the pleasure of staying at Le Meridien, Dubai on our way back to Australia from Europe. Our first impression of the hotel was bright, open and airy and also rather unexpectedly, friendly. As we arrived very early in the morning our room was not quite ready for us - but never mind - would we like a complimentary drink and a chance to read a paper whilst we waited? Reception staff were pleasant and then when we were escorted to our room - all of the amenities of the hotel and room were explained to us. We quickly washed and changed - eager not to miss a moment of this experience and headed out for a walk in the open air before it got much hotter. When we returned to our room we found that we had been left a lovely, chilled fruit basket and our air conditioning had been turned on to a pleasantly cool level. Pools and gardens duly inspected we were suitably impressed except that there was a very limited amount of shade poolside. Important for a traveller who has to visit their skin doctor every three months to have sun spots removed. We passed the day lazing around, checking out the restaurants of which there are 14 in different areas of the hotel. We wandered the gardens and marvelled at the cleanliness of them all. In the evening after a couple of glasses of perfectly made G&amp;T we decided that we might indulge in the seafood buffet (every Tuesday night) in the Yalumba Restaurant. Were we ever in for a treat! Not exactly big seafood eaters we had so many prawns that we couldn't believe we had actually eaten so many. They were cooked in every way imaginable, chilly, tempura, garlic, stir fried, bbq, and even fresh. With freshly schucked oysters, mussels, baby fish and so many other dishes in fact too many to even remember, let alone list, we rounded out our delicious meal with some BBQ lobster tails. Desserts (yes we still had room) were to die for and, then when we finally decided that we should leave before we exploded we ordered coffee which was accompanied by freshly cooked individual chocolate souffles. My husband (a chocoholic) actually declined his souffle because he was so full) but couldn't resist a dip of a spoon into the warm, runny, heavenly, chocolate sauce at the bottom of my souffle). We have told a number of people about this experience in the weeks that we have been home and by this review hope that many more travellers get to visit this lovely hotel, chat to the friendly staff, and get to enjoy one of the very best meals this wonderful world of ours can offer. PS outside dining was also an option, which was great for those who enjoy a cigarette with dinner or families with children who like to make a bit of noise whilst enjoying themselves. A night to remember - and in the morning your would never have known that a very large party had taken place. Grounds were hosed and gardens and sand freshly raked and not a prawn shell or smell was visible come breakfast. We wish Le Meridien well and continued success.	
