Nov 1 2006 	couldn't ask for more	I Stayed in this hotel for a week in october 2006 with my fiancee and I can't say enough good things about it...When we arrived late evening i made sure i asked for a room by one of the pools inward facing and not outward (after reading various reviews on here), we were duly issued the key to a room on the ground floor with french doors opening onto one of the courtyards about 25 yards from the pool itself, perfect. The rooms are spot on for 99% of the population of the world, I can imagine some people might find a problem with them but only those used to the penthouse suite at the ritz as standard. Our room had a plasma, dvd player and all the things you would expect including italian coffee machine. About 10 minutes after we arrived there was a knock on the door and we were issued with a bowl of fresh fruit and a couple of bottles of fresh water, the fruit lasted all week and the water was replenished every day, gratis.There was some building work going on during our stay, but to be honest, it really wasn't a problem, i just wished i'd seen it complete because what they were doing looked quite good.Days by the pool were great, whichever pool you do choose to hang out at you are met with a stress free, quiet, laid back atmosphere which compliments the surroundings and the service at the various pool bars is quite excellent.Food...where do i start....there are some 14 restaurants dotted around the hotel and a couple can eat for about £50-00 all in including drinks at almost all of them except the australian restaurant which serves a higher class of food probably only matched by gordon ramsey. I highly recommend the nightly outdoor buffet which works out at about £25-00 per head for all you can eat and drink, and when i mean drink i mean ANY drink you want and not cheap varieties. If i wanted gin and tonic, the gin was bombay sapphire, i think you get the drift. Food wise, the style rotates every night and can be tex-mex or carribbean or german depending on the perticular evening.One day of the holiday we decided to visit one of the sister hotels on the beach, i knew there would be a fee, and to be honest i really didn't care, you pay alot less to stay at le meridien at the airport so a fee of £15-00 per person to go to the beach isn't bad at all. I asked at reception and they told me the better of the two pool wise is the royal meridien so we hopped on the free shuttle at 10am and headed down there. On arrival we were handed towels and taken down to the beach on a golf buggy to save walking, during the day we were handed cold sprays and cool ice fruit shots to cool us down. The ammount of work going on around the beach hotel is awe enspiring and for someone like myself it really wasn't an issue, to be visiting the city in a time where it is literally srpinging up around you is quite special. At 4pm we were picked back up and taken back to the hotel, the traffic is pretty bad but i wouldn't say it was any worse than any typical english city at rush hour.Overall, with various trips out at night, the burj, grovenor house etc (buddha bar and bar 44 as classy as they come) i would say that this was one of the best and most relaxing holidays that i have ever had and 99% of that, i would say, is down to Le Meridien Dubai and the fantastic service that they gave us the whole time that we were there. We will be back.Oh, and one last thing, i read most of the reviews on this site about le meridien and to be honest after reading some of them i nearly cancelled because they were so negative. After visiting, i would now assume that these are the type of people who would visit their friend's homes with white gloves on to test for dust and when they found it they would tut loudly. Trust me, ignore these people and stay here, it's a perfect place to be.	
Oct 25 2006 	A peaceful and pleasant stay with excellent service and a warm welcome	My husband and I stayed at Le Meridien in early October 2006 on a trip to celebrate his 30th birthday and we thought it was a great hotel. I had checked reviews before I booked the trip as I was a little concerned about the hotel's proximity to the airport but as with other reviewers we experienced no problems with noise and we rarely heard or saw planes overhead. We took the free shuttle bus from the airport to the hotel - the service was very quick and the bus was in fact a very plush and shiny new people carrier which gave us a clue as to what to expect at the hotel!On arrival we were welcomed by name before we had even checked in and all the staff were very friendly. Our room was immaculate and had all the amenities we needed including a flat widescreen tv and dvd player (so take your own dvds if you have time to kill or kids to entertain). We stayed during Ramadan and had no problems eating during daylight hours although we made good use of room service out of respect for locals. The room service was very impressive - the food is rolled in on a table, already laid out with plates, cutlery and flowers, and the food is kept in a heated container underneath the table cloth. The staff set up the table, chairs and food for us and made sure we had everything we needed. Food was pretty reasonably priced and the menu had a real mix of food on offer.We made good use of the concierge service which was very helpful and we booked a desert safari through the business centre where staff were also on hand to answer all our questions. During our spare time we used the pools which had the most comfortable sunbeds I've ever laid on (!) and was lovely and peaceful, not overcrowded like some hotels we've stayed in. There was even a jacuzzi outside which was strangely very relaxing in the hot weather! There was some rennovations going on during our stay but we were unaffected by them and didn't feel like our stay was marred in any way. The hotel is a further out of town than some of the other hotels however taxis were plentiful and fairly inexpensive so we didn't feel that this was a hinderance, in fact being so close to the airport was great come check out since we got more time in bed! The only minor complaints we had were that the shuttle service into town wasn't more regular and that there could have been a few more vegetarian options on the room service menu. All in all we were really impressed by both the staff and the hotel - something that was reinforced when we got home and had an email from the hotel following up on the feedback we'd left and letting us know that they were taking steps to improve the areas we had commented on. It just showed what good customer service they provide, which I reckon has to be the mark of a good hotel. I'd definitely stay here again if I ever return to Dubai in the future. Oh and a top tip for any visitor to Dubai: make sure you book afternoon tea at the Skyview Bar in the Burj Al Arab - the views are amazing and the food is scrumptious! And if you can afford it make a reservation for dinner at their Al Mahara seafood restaurant - it's definitely a unique dining experience!	
